00:00:20.527 --> 00:00:27.380
PROFESSOR: Let's go
back to our discussion

00:00:27.380 --> 00:00:30.430
of spectral broadening.

00:00:30.430 --> 00:00:33.780
And what I started
to derive for you

00:00:33.780 --> 00:00:39.310
is perturbation theory of
spectral broadening, which

00:00:39.310 --> 00:00:42.190
is a very general framework.

00:00:42.190 --> 00:00:45.182
I like it, because
it really provides

00:00:45.182 --> 00:00:47.530
you insight into
spectral broadening.

00:00:47.530 --> 00:00:51.270
But I will also hope it
provides new insight for you

00:00:51.270 --> 00:00:54.670
for time-dependent perturbation
theory [INAUDIBLE].

00:00:54.670 --> 00:01:00.590
So what we did in
this lecture is

00:01:00.590 --> 00:01:05.370
we pretty much did standard
type perturbation theory.

00:01:05.370 --> 00:01:07.773
We just did it by
assuming that we

00:01:07.773 --> 00:01:10.210
have a general
time-dependent perturbation.

00:01:10.210 --> 00:01:12.910
I'm not yet telling you what the
time-dependent perturbation is.

00:01:12.910 --> 00:01:14.076
It has actually fluctuating.

00:01:14.076 --> 00:01:15.384
It has inhomogeneous.

00:01:15.384 --> 00:01:17.760
It has everything in
it which will later

00:01:17.760 --> 00:01:21.250
lead to line-broadening
line shifts.

00:01:21.250 --> 00:01:28.470
And the important quantity which
is now describing everything

00:01:28.470 --> 00:01:31.872
we are interested
is the correlation

00:01:31.872 --> 00:01:35.500
function between the
perturbation at time t

00:01:35.500 --> 00:01:38.020
pi and t.

00:01:38.020 --> 00:01:42.030
And we call this
correlation function G.

00:01:42.030 --> 00:01:44.360
And it is either the
correlation function G of t,

00:01:44.360 --> 00:01:47.820
or it's Fourier
transform, which tells us

00:01:47.820 --> 00:01:49.950
what the excitation
rate of the system is.

00:01:59.570 --> 00:02:03.930
I want to give you sort
of two summaries now.

00:02:08.154 --> 00:02:10.539
And they're both general
to perturbation theory.

00:02:10.539 --> 00:02:14.610
But I have to say, I
myself learned something

00:02:14.610 --> 00:02:18.870
about time evolution of quantum
systems from those examples.

00:02:18.870 --> 00:02:21.295
So what we get is a
very generic thing,

00:02:21.295 --> 00:02:23.753
that when we look
at the probability

00:02:23.753 --> 00:02:28.220
to be in the final state,
the amplitude V of t squared,

00:02:28.220 --> 00:02:31.226
we start out quadratic, a very
general behavior of any quantum

00:02:31.226 --> 00:02:34.990
system, because your linear
equation, which linearly

00:02:34.990 --> 00:02:38.430
puts amplitude into the
excited state is quadratic.

00:02:38.430 --> 00:02:41.526
And also, this is the beginning
of a Rabi oscillation.

00:02:41.526 --> 00:02:45.290
The Rabi oscillation
starts out with 0 slope.

00:02:45.290 --> 00:02:49.280
But then you have some
de-coherence type.

00:02:49.280 --> 00:02:53.140
The fields are no longer driving
the system in a coherent way.

00:02:53.140 --> 00:02:56.710
And then that's where we
enter the regime of Fermi's

00:02:56.710 --> 00:02:59.930
golden rule, the probability
to be in the excited state

00:02:59.930 --> 00:03:01.770
only goes linear.

00:03:01.770 --> 00:03:05.570
And this is when we
have rate equations.

00:03:05.570 --> 00:03:10.620
Let me sort of show how it
comes about in equations,

00:03:10.620 --> 00:03:12.725
which I think is really nice.

00:03:12.725 --> 00:03:21.312
The differential equations
is that in a time delta t,

00:03:21.312 --> 00:03:25.150
we add amplitude delta
t to the excited state.

00:03:25.150 --> 00:03:28.210
And so the amplitude
we build up is--

00:03:28.210 --> 00:03:30.410
I may have called an h bar.

00:03:30.410 --> 00:03:34.120
Or maybe I measured
[INAUDIBLE] frequency units.

00:03:34.120 --> 00:03:37.600
It's just the matrix
element times delta t.

00:03:37.600 --> 00:03:39.790
And we usually call
the matrix element

00:03:39.790 --> 00:03:41.350
the Rabi frequency over 2.

00:03:41.350 --> 00:03:43.410
So you should think
about it, that we

00:03:43.410 --> 00:03:45.800
add sort of this amplitude.

00:03:45.800 --> 00:03:47.997
And as long as we
are coherent, I

00:03:47.997 --> 00:03:51.744
have to take the amplitude
1/2 the Rabi frequency delta,

00:03:51.744 --> 00:03:53.130
then square it.

00:03:53.130 --> 00:03:56.650
And here, you get the
quadratic behavior.

00:03:56.650 --> 00:04:01.160
This behavior you also have
constructive interference.

00:04:01.160 --> 00:04:05.062
All those delta [INAUDIBLE] are
added in a phase-coherent way.

00:04:05.062 --> 00:04:09.555
But this behavior ends, of
course, at the coherence time.

00:04:19.110 --> 00:04:20.515
Let me just get my notes.

00:04:31.030 --> 00:04:36.600
So when the time becomes
comparable to the coherence

00:04:36.600 --> 00:04:48.370
time, then we are adding
amplitude not as constructive

00:04:48.370 --> 00:04:52.580
interference-- we are
adding B squared [INAUDIBLE]

00:04:52.580 --> 00:04:54.420
becomes sort of a
[INAUDIBLE], and we

00:04:54.420 --> 00:04:56.560
add things in quadrature.

00:04:56.560 --> 00:05:02.925
So what happens is at
the coherence time,

00:05:02.925 --> 00:05:08.980
we have created
an amplitude which

00:05:08.980 --> 00:05:12.580
is given by this expression.

00:05:16.461 --> 00:05:22.760
But now if time goes by,
we add in quadrature t

00:05:22.760 --> 00:05:26.350
over tc chunks of that.

00:05:26.350 --> 00:05:31.560
So therefore, our B square,
which we build up with time,

00:05:31.560 --> 00:05:36.270
is linear in time
and is omega Rabi

00:05:36.270 --> 00:05:39.980
squared over 4, the matrix
element times the coherence

00:05:39.980 --> 00:05:40.715
time tc.

00:05:44.200 --> 00:05:48.720
And this here now is our
rate in the rate equation.

00:05:51.440 --> 00:05:56.090
And this is also what
we exactly got out

00:05:56.090 --> 00:06:00.680
of the correlation
function formalism.

00:06:00.680 --> 00:06:02.490
So this is how you
should think about it.

00:06:02.490 --> 00:06:04.200
You go from constructive
interference

00:06:04.200 --> 00:06:07.350
in amplitude and adding
things in quadrature.

00:06:07.350 --> 00:06:14.560
Let me maybe add one more
discussion to it, which I hope

00:06:14.560 --> 00:06:18.500
will help you to
see the big picture.

00:06:18.500 --> 00:06:21.900
We have a matrix
element V. And if I just

00:06:21.900 --> 00:06:24.720
ask you, think about
Fermi's golden rule,

00:06:24.720 --> 00:06:27.890
you would find out
that the rate is

00:06:27.890 --> 00:06:34.910
V square times the density
of states at the resonance.

00:06:34.910 --> 00:06:38.890
And sometimes instead of
the density of states,

00:06:38.890 --> 00:06:43.200
you write a delta function,
which is just a placeholder

00:06:43.200 --> 00:06:45.044
that you should do
an energy integral.

00:06:45.044 --> 00:06:47.818
And then you get the
density of states.

00:06:47.818 --> 00:06:48.730
OK.

00:06:48.730 --> 00:06:50.590
So this is sort of
Fermi's golden rule,

00:06:50.590 --> 00:06:53.180
and it should be old hat to you.

00:06:53.180 --> 00:07:05.940
But what I told you now is
that what is involved here

00:07:05.940 --> 00:07:11.340
from the time integration is the
correlation function, V of 0,

00:07:11.340 --> 00:07:14.300
V of t as two different types.

00:07:14.300 --> 00:07:16.220
But then because of
the type integration

00:07:16.220 --> 00:07:21.090
of Schrodinger's equation,
we had a time integral dt.

00:07:21.090 --> 00:07:26.590
But V of 0, V of t, remember,
we have a correlation

00:07:26.590 --> 00:07:28.150
between the field V of 0.

00:07:28.150 --> 00:07:30.470
And then it decays with time.

00:07:30.470 --> 00:07:34.700
This here can be written
V of 0 squared times

00:07:34.700 --> 00:07:38.190
the correlation time tau c.

00:07:38.190 --> 00:07:40.860
So therefore, the
correlation function,

00:07:40.860 --> 00:07:42.060
it's a general formalism.

00:07:42.060 --> 00:07:44.990
It allows us to deal with
all time dependencies.

00:07:44.990 --> 00:07:48.130
But in essence, the
time-integrated correlation

00:07:48.130 --> 00:07:51.064
function is nothing
else than your operator,

00:07:51.064 --> 00:07:52.480
your perturbation
operator, time t

00:07:52.480 --> 00:07:56.240
equals 0 squared times
the correlation time.

00:07:56.240 --> 00:07:59.160
And the correlation time, the
inverse of the correlation

00:07:59.160 --> 00:08:03.500
time, is the spectral
widths of your drive field.

00:08:03.500 --> 00:08:05.390
And this is what
the spectral widths

00:08:05.390 --> 00:08:10.310
is in Fermi's golden rule.

00:08:10.310 --> 00:08:14.990
On the other hand, if you do
the integration V of t dt,

00:08:14.990 --> 00:08:17.610
think about it as
Fourier transform,

00:08:17.610 --> 00:08:21.640
it gives us actually
some V of omega.

00:08:21.640 --> 00:08:24.560
It gives us the
Fourier transform.

00:08:24.560 --> 00:08:26.350
Well, I see it omega.

00:08:26.350 --> 00:08:29.440
If you just do V of t
dt, you get the Fourier

00:08:29.440 --> 00:08:31.131
transform at 0 frequency.

00:08:31.131 --> 00:08:32.714
But if you look
through the derivation

00:08:32.714 --> 00:08:35.350
we did that was an
e to the i omega

00:08:35.350 --> 00:08:38.559
resonant term, which we
were just spitting out.

00:08:38.559 --> 00:08:41.309
So we have sort of shifted
the origin of frequency.

00:08:41.309 --> 00:08:43.695
So therefore, the
Fourier transform,

00:08:43.695 --> 00:08:46.580
if I correct for this just
offset infrequency which

00:08:46.580 --> 00:08:50.240
I introduced for
simplicity, this

00:08:50.240 --> 00:08:57.010
is nothing else than asking
whether the drive field has

00:08:57.010 --> 00:08:59.280
a Fourier component
which can resonate

00:08:59.280 --> 00:09:00.900
the drive to transition.

00:09:00.900 --> 00:09:03.850
And we talked last class
about the convolution.

00:09:03.850 --> 00:09:05.880
This gives actually
the power spectrum.

00:09:05.880 --> 00:09:09.700
It keeps the Fourier
transform of it squared.

00:09:09.700 --> 00:09:14.060
But the power spectrum is, of
course-- when you take a field

00:09:14.060 --> 00:09:15.560
and fully analyze
it, [INAUDIBLE]

00:09:15.560 --> 00:09:20.430
is the power spectrum, the whole
power and the whole intensity

00:09:20.430 --> 00:09:22.800
of your laser, of your
field is spread out

00:09:22.800 --> 00:09:24.560
over the banquets of the source.

00:09:24.560 --> 00:09:28.040
So when you say, the power
spectrum, the power spectrum

00:09:28.040 --> 00:09:32.652
is automatically intensity
divided by spectral widths.

00:09:32.652 --> 00:09:34.110
And that's where
the delta function

00:09:34.110 --> 00:09:37.090
and the spectral widths in the
normal formulation of Fermi's

00:09:37.090 --> 00:09:38.840
golden rule come in.

00:09:38.840 --> 00:09:41.420
So I'm just emphasizing
I haven't really

00:09:41.420 --> 00:09:46.170
done anything new than just
giving you a general notation.

00:09:46.170 --> 00:09:48.070
And I would actually
say-- whenever

00:09:48.070 --> 00:09:50.640
you were asking yourself
about Fermi's golden rule,

00:09:50.640 --> 00:09:52.020
this is the full [INAUDIBLE].

00:09:52.020 --> 00:09:54.851
This is about a fully
time-dependent arbitrary time

00:09:54.851 --> 00:09:55.350
field.

00:09:55.350 --> 00:10:00.330
And you realize, what was
re-squaring Fermi's golden rule

00:10:00.330 --> 00:10:04.050
is actually just
the simple case,

00:10:04.050 --> 00:10:06.360
the more general case--
and the more general case

00:10:06.360 --> 00:10:09.950
is it's a correlation
or it's a power spectrum

00:10:09.950 --> 00:10:13.820
which creates the rate
in Fermi's golden rule.

00:10:16.595 --> 00:10:17.636
Any questions about that?

00:10:21.291 --> 00:10:21.790
OK.

00:10:21.790 --> 00:10:26.089
So we have this
powerful formalism.

00:10:26.089 --> 00:10:28.380
So all we have to do is when
we want to understand what

00:10:28.380 --> 00:10:30.720
is the rate and
the spectral widths

00:10:30.720 --> 00:10:32.820
of the spectroscopic
features is we

00:10:32.820 --> 00:10:38.490
have to understand what is
the field driving the atom.

00:10:38.490 --> 00:10:41.500
And then we take the
Fourier transform,

00:10:41.500 --> 00:10:43.490
or we figure out what
the correlation is.

00:10:43.490 --> 00:10:46.450
We take V of 0 squared
times the correlation time,

00:10:46.450 --> 00:10:48.730
and we know what the rate is.

00:10:48.730 --> 00:10:51.100
And this will allow
us major insight

00:10:51.100 --> 00:10:54.330
into spectral broadening.

00:10:54.330 --> 00:10:55.260
OK.

00:10:55.260 --> 00:10:59.245
But after introducing
that in general,

00:10:59.245 --> 00:11:02.230
I think it's time
for a simple example.

00:11:02.230 --> 00:11:04.850
And as a simple
example, I just thought

00:11:04.850 --> 00:11:08.590
I'd show you how we get
the natural line widths.

00:11:08.590 --> 00:11:11.000
And of course, the
natural line widths--

00:11:11.000 --> 00:11:14.000
I've mentioned several times,
we need Optical Bloch equations.

00:11:14.000 --> 00:11:15.780
We have to really
kind of capture

00:11:15.780 --> 00:11:18.410
the interplay between
the coherent drive

00:11:18.410 --> 00:11:20.910
of the atom and the
spontaneous decay.

00:11:20.910 --> 00:11:22.900
But just
phenomenologically, if I

00:11:22.900 --> 00:11:28.410
say the excited state has a
decay rate of gamma over 2,

00:11:28.410 --> 00:11:30.000
I mentioned it
before, we can capture

00:11:30.000 --> 00:11:33.740
some aspects of
spontaneous decay.

00:11:33.740 --> 00:11:37.990
And that means now,
remember, our spectral widths

00:11:37.990 --> 00:11:40.830
comes from the correlation
function of the matrix element.

00:11:40.830 --> 00:11:43.160
And now the operator
is constant,

00:11:43.160 --> 00:11:44.970
but the state is decaying.

00:11:44.970 --> 00:11:49.470
So therefore, the matrix element
has this exponentially decaying

00:11:49.470 --> 00:11:50.620
function.

00:11:50.620 --> 00:11:53.100
And if you then ask,
what is the correlation

00:11:53.100 --> 00:11:56.650
function at time 0 and
time tau, we get this.

00:12:02.440 --> 00:12:05.590
Of course, the Fourier transform
of an exponentially decaying

00:12:05.590 --> 00:12:07.400
function is a Lorentian.

00:12:07.400 --> 00:12:11.630
And I've shown you now with a
different formalism that yes,

00:12:11.630 --> 00:12:14.680
if you have dampening in the
excited state, for instance,

00:12:14.680 --> 00:12:20.980
you do spontaneous decay,
we get the Lorentian.

00:12:20.980 --> 00:12:23.470
Of course, we know there should
be power broadening, too.

00:12:23.470 --> 00:12:26.020
But of course, don't
expect power broadening

00:12:26.020 --> 00:12:29.180
from a perturbative approach,
because a perturbative approach

00:12:29.180 --> 00:12:33.330
is only valid when we
have weak drive fields.

00:12:39.586 --> 00:12:42.580
Questions?

00:12:42.580 --> 00:12:43.900
OK.

00:12:43.900 --> 00:12:48.236
So now I want to-- after
this simple example,

00:12:48.236 --> 00:12:50.100
I want to explain to
you Doppler broadening.

00:12:57.210 --> 00:12:59.250
I know I will
present it in a way

00:12:59.250 --> 00:13:06.143
and draw some conclusions
which are usually not done

00:13:06.143 --> 00:13:09.540
in the normal presentation
of Doppler broadening.

00:13:09.540 --> 00:13:18.270
So what we have to bring in now
is that we have moving atoms.

00:13:18.270 --> 00:13:20.764
That's what Doppler
broadening is about.

00:13:24.390 --> 00:13:28.270
We drive the field with
an electromagnetic wave.

00:13:28.270 --> 00:13:33.180
And we have usually ignored
the spatial dependence,

00:13:33.180 --> 00:13:37.700
assuming the atom was
clamped down in c equals 0.

00:13:37.700 --> 00:13:40.960
But now we have to
allow for motion.

00:13:40.960 --> 00:13:44.760
So the relevant matrix
element for which

00:13:44.760 --> 00:13:49.570
we want to calculate
the correlation function

00:13:49.570 --> 00:13:51.065
has now a spatial dependence.

00:13:53.740 --> 00:13:58.722
And our correlation
function, G of ba,

00:13:58.722 --> 00:14:05.720
involves now-- I call
the Rabi frequency now

00:14:05.720 --> 00:14:15.470
x for, well, simplicity
of-- [INAUDIBLE]

00:14:15.470 --> 00:14:17.911
took this material,
because they use it.

00:14:17.911 --> 00:14:18.410
OK.

00:14:18.410 --> 00:14:20.640
So now we have the
correlation function.

00:14:20.640 --> 00:14:27.100
We have the temporal
part, t prime minus t.

00:14:27.100 --> 00:14:28.880
But then we have a spatial part.

00:14:28.880 --> 00:14:31.300
And this is now
the new part which

00:14:31.300 --> 00:14:38.586
has to account for that the
atom is moving from one position

00:14:38.586 --> 00:14:39.578
to another one.

00:14:44.010 --> 00:14:47.390
And when we calculate
the correlation function,

00:14:47.390 --> 00:14:50.525
we have to average
now over the velocity

00:14:50.525 --> 00:14:51.794
distribution of the atom.

00:14:54.450 --> 00:15:00.560
So this new part, which will
account for Doppler broadening,

00:15:00.560 --> 00:15:07.370
I called this part I. And
z of t prime minus z of t

00:15:07.370 --> 00:15:12.882
is simply the velocity
of the atom times tau.

00:15:12.882 --> 00:15:15.250
Tau is t prime minus t.

00:15:15.250 --> 00:15:19.530
So atoms move by that.

00:15:19.530 --> 00:15:25.940
And v is the z component
of the velocity.

00:15:25.940 --> 00:15:28.680
So now we have to
calculate that.

00:15:28.680 --> 00:15:31.930
And of course, we
assume that we have

00:15:31.930 --> 00:15:33.400
a Maxwell-Boltzmann
distribution.

00:15:40.550 --> 00:15:43.560
We assume a Maxwell-Boltzmann
distribution.

00:15:46.430 --> 00:15:51.420
And then our
expression I, we have

00:15:51.420 --> 00:15:58.900
to convolute-- we have
this term, e to the kv tau.

00:15:58.900 --> 00:16:02.380
But now we have to
convolute it with

00:16:02.380 --> 00:16:07.110
the one-dimensional
Maxwell-Boltzmann distribution,

00:16:07.110 --> 00:16:09.550
where alpha is the
most probable velocity.

00:16:12.202 --> 00:16:15.300
And since the velocity
distribution is normalized,

00:16:15.300 --> 00:16:24.230
we have this p [? vector. ?]
Alpha is the most probable

00:16:24.230 --> 00:16:31.596
speed, and mu is the mass
of the-- sorry, it's not mu,

00:16:31.596 --> 00:16:33.193
it's M. And M is the
mass of the atom.

00:16:40.600 --> 00:16:44.240
This integral, of course,
can easily be solved.

00:16:44.240 --> 00:16:59.165
And we find that provides--
[INAUDIBLE] Gaussian envelope

00:16:59.165 --> 00:17:03.530
with time tau, so it's
exponential-decayed with time

00:17:03.530 --> 00:17:05.630
tau.

00:17:05.630 --> 00:17:16.470
And our rate, which
is the matrix element,

00:17:16.470 --> 00:17:24.970
involves now the
temporal integral over--

00:17:24.970 --> 00:17:26.060
let me just scroll up.

00:17:28.780 --> 00:17:31.680
In our correlation function,
we had a temporal part

00:17:31.680 --> 00:17:33.390
and a spatial part.

00:17:33.390 --> 00:17:36.318
And the rate-- this was
Fermi's golden rule--

00:17:36.318 --> 00:17:38.568
is the time we've taken over
the correlation function.

00:17:44.010 --> 00:17:51.120
So therefore, we have the
exponential [? vector ?]

00:17:51.120 --> 00:17:52.710
in time.

00:17:52.710 --> 00:17:58.970
After convolution with the
Maxwell-Boltzmann distribution,

00:17:58.970 --> 00:18:02.870
we have this exponentially
decaying term.

00:18:02.870 --> 00:18:06.046
And the result of
that is, well, hooray,

00:18:06.046 --> 00:18:10.610
we have re-derived
the Gaussian profile

00:18:10.610 --> 00:18:13.112
for a Doppler broad light.

00:18:24.230 --> 00:18:25.130
OK.

00:18:25.130 --> 00:18:33.080
But yes, we want to look at
this result with some new eyes,

00:18:33.080 --> 00:18:35.400
because until now,
you would have said,

00:18:35.400 --> 00:18:36.540
OK, that's really trivial.

00:18:36.540 --> 00:18:38.150
Each atom has a velocity.

00:18:38.150 --> 00:18:41.040
Galilean transformation
into the moving frame

00:18:41.040 --> 00:18:43.680
means the frequency has shifted,
and everything falls together.

00:18:43.680 --> 00:18:45.356
And yes, that's one
way to look at it.

00:18:45.356 --> 00:18:49.400
In inhomogeneous broadening,
each atom has its own velocity.

00:18:49.400 --> 00:18:52.220
But now we want to look
at it from the viewpoint

00:18:52.220 --> 00:18:56.750
of a correlation function
describing the whole system.

00:18:56.750 --> 00:19:01.820
So we had calculated this
correlation function,

00:19:01.820 --> 00:19:04.870
which the atomic
ensemble experiences.

00:19:04.870 --> 00:19:08.405
And this correlation
function here

00:19:08.405 --> 00:19:12.420
decays as a function of time.

00:19:12.420 --> 00:19:16.235
And it decays with a
characteristic time.

00:19:24.660 --> 00:19:30.510
Tau c, which is 1 over k alpha.

00:19:30.510 --> 00:19:35.180
And this is nothing else than
the reduced wavelengths lambda

00:19:35.180 --> 00:19:38.210
bar divided by the
most probable velocity.

00:19:42.846 --> 00:19:43.600
OK.

00:19:43.600 --> 00:19:49.580
So we want to relate
the line widths

00:19:49.580 --> 00:19:52.500
to some form of coherence.

00:19:52.500 --> 00:19:54.495
And what we realize
is the coherence

00:19:54.495 --> 00:19:57.470
time of the correlation
function, which needs Doppler

00:19:57.470 --> 00:20:03.740
broadening, is the time it takes
an atom with the most probably

00:20:03.740 --> 00:20:07.600
velocity to move one wavelength.

00:20:07.600 --> 00:20:10.290
But wait.

00:20:10.290 --> 00:20:12.990
What we have is, in the
Maxwell-Boltzmann distribution,

00:20:12.990 --> 00:20:15.890
the most probably
velocity is also

00:20:15.890 --> 00:20:19.230
the widths of the velocities.

00:20:19.230 --> 00:20:23.670
So therefore, what we can say
is, if all the atoms would

00:20:23.670 --> 00:20:27.600
start at one position, after
the correlation time tc,

00:20:27.600 --> 00:20:33.250
the atoms have spread
out over one wavelength.

00:20:33.250 --> 00:20:35.400
So therefore, the
correlation time

00:20:35.400 --> 00:20:41.070
tells us how long is the whole
ensemble driven coherently.

00:20:41.070 --> 00:20:43.410
But once the atoms,
due to their motion,

00:20:43.410 --> 00:20:46.770
spread out compared to
their initial position,

00:20:46.770 --> 00:20:49.370
while extra
wavelengths, each atom

00:20:49.370 --> 00:20:53.555
experiences now a different
phase of the drive field.

00:20:57.130 --> 00:20:59.820
And that sets a limit
to the coherence.

00:20:59.820 --> 00:21:02.750
And this is the point where
when we ask how many atoms

00:21:02.750 --> 00:21:07.970
are getting excited, we
can no longer add amplitude

00:21:07.970 --> 00:21:09.430
in a constructive, linear way.

00:21:09.430 --> 00:21:11.820
We are adding amplitudes
in quadrature.

00:21:11.820 --> 00:21:13.639
And this is exactly
what I explained to you

00:21:13.639 --> 00:21:15.014
at the beginning
of this lecture.

00:21:18.630 --> 00:21:20.310
So let me just summarize it.

00:21:20.310 --> 00:21:26.140
Alpha is the thermal
spread of velocities.

00:21:37.600 --> 00:21:40.720
So the keyword is here.

00:21:40.720 --> 00:21:50.370
Atoms, in a random way,
spread out by lambda

00:21:50.370 --> 00:21:53.124
in the coherence time tc.

00:22:01.890 --> 00:22:05.310
Well, a question which should
come to your mind is now,

00:22:05.310 --> 00:22:09.225
but what happens when the atoms
are in an atom [INAUDIBLE]

00:22:09.225 --> 00:22:11.840
and they cannot spread out?

00:22:11.840 --> 00:22:14.520
That's what you want to
discuss in a few minutes.

00:22:14.520 --> 00:22:17.110
But before I do
that, let me give you

00:22:17.110 --> 00:22:28.940
another interpretation,
which is helpful.

00:22:28.940 --> 00:22:32.200
You can regard-- if you
have a thermal ensemble,

00:22:32.200 --> 00:22:33.640
you can say, OK, I have a box.

00:22:33.640 --> 00:22:38.230
Each atom is a plain wave
with a perfect velocity,

00:22:38.230 --> 00:22:40.430
and now an ensemble of that.

00:22:40.430 --> 00:22:44.420
But very often, especially
if you do localized physics,

00:22:44.420 --> 00:22:48.170
you want to regard each
atom as a wave packet.

00:22:48.170 --> 00:22:51.210
And if you want to use
a localized description

00:22:51.210 --> 00:23:01.710
of your gas, where
atoms are wave packets,

00:23:01.710 --> 00:23:07.080
then you assume, in a
consistent description,

00:23:07.080 --> 00:23:11.350
that the atoms are spread out
due to the momentum spread

00:23:11.350 --> 00:23:13.990
in the Maxwell-Boltzmann
distribution.

00:23:13.990 --> 00:23:19.230
This is nothing else
than h bar divided

00:23:19.230 --> 00:23:22.786
by the mass and the most
[INAUDIBLE] velocity.

00:23:22.786 --> 00:23:25.500
And this is foregoing
[? vectors ?]

00:23:25.500 --> 00:23:30.665
on the order of unity, nothing
else than the thermal de

00:23:30.665 --> 00:23:33.530
Broglie wavelengths.

00:23:33.530 --> 00:23:34.340
OK.

00:23:34.340 --> 00:23:37.190
So now we have the
picture that the atom

00:23:37.190 --> 00:23:39.840
is a wave packet in
the ground state.

00:23:39.840 --> 00:23:42.985
But now we excite
it with a laser.

00:23:42.985 --> 00:23:50.450
Well, if we excite it with a
laser, part of the wave packet

00:23:50.450 --> 00:23:52.880
goes to the excited state.

00:23:52.880 --> 00:23:56.110
But the atoms in
the excited state,

00:23:56.110 --> 00:24:00.130
because they have absorbed the
photon recall of the photon,

00:24:00.130 --> 00:24:04.320
are now moving away
from the ground state

00:24:04.320 --> 00:24:07.625
part of the wave packet,
with the recall velocity,

00:24:07.625 --> 00:24:12.100
with this h bar k over M.

00:24:12.100 --> 00:24:13.800
So if I regard
the atom as a wave

00:24:13.800 --> 00:24:17.450
packet, the natural
question is, when

00:24:17.450 --> 00:24:20.770
does the ground state
of the wave packet

00:24:20.770 --> 00:24:24.332
lose overlap with the excited
state part of the wave packet?

00:24:32.270 --> 00:24:40.716
Lost overlap after time--
well, I derive it for you.

00:24:40.716 --> 00:24:43.500
But it can only be
the coherence time.

00:24:43.500 --> 00:24:54.550
So the time is the
size of the wave packet

00:24:54.550 --> 00:25:01.150
divided by the recall velocity.

00:25:01.150 --> 00:25:02.380
The mass cancels out.

00:25:02.380 --> 00:25:04.070
H bar cancels out.

00:25:04.070 --> 00:25:07.570
And this is 1 over k alpha.

00:25:07.570 --> 00:25:11.930
And this was exactly
our coherence time.

00:25:11.930 --> 00:25:14.130
So therefore, when
I'm telling you

00:25:14.130 --> 00:25:18.250
you should understand
this picture,

00:25:18.250 --> 00:25:25.710
Doppler broadening is a loss
of coherence for the ensemble.

00:25:25.710 --> 00:25:29.150
You have now two
ways to describe it.

00:25:29.150 --> 00:25:34.350
One is you can say, in a
more quantum mechanical way,

00:25:34.350 --> 00:25:40.410
after the coherence
time, the recall velocity

00:25:40.410 --> 00:25:43.490
has separated the
grounded, excited part

00:25:43.490 --> 00:25:44.825
of your wave packet.

00:25:49.560 --> 00:25:54.750
Or you can say, when the
atoms in the ensemble

00:25:54.750 --> 00:25:57.762
have a velocity
spread of alpha, then

00:25:57.762 --> 00:26:02.740
they have spread out by
the optical wavelengths.

00:26:02.740 --> 00:26:04.750
So these are two
equivalent picture

00:26:04.750 --> 00:26:09.188
to understand why this ensemble
is no longer coherently driven.

00:26:12.972 --> 00:26:13.472
Yes?

00:26:13.472 --> 00:26:18.169
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE] in both
of the curves, like, why is,

00:26:18.169 --> 00:26:20.168
in the first picture, the
optical wavelength not

00:26:20.168 --> 00:26:23.500
relevant; in the second one,
[INAUDIBLE] not relevant?

00:26:23.500 --> 00:26:26.356
[INAUDIBLE] distance.

00:26:26.356 --> 00:26:31.890
PROFESSOR: Well, because these
