00:26:33.865 --> 00:26:37.314
I mean, the wavelength comes
into the picture with the wave

00:26:37.314 --> 00:26:39.510
packets through the
recall velocity,

00:26:39.510 --> 00:26:42.666
because the recall
velocity is h bar k over M,

00:26:42.666 --> 00:26:44.270
and k is the
inverse wavelengths.

00:26:44.270 --> 00:26:45.138
AUDIENCE: Right.

00:26:45.138 --> 00:26:48.310
But when we write delta t
there, we write [INAUDIBLE]

00:26:48.310 --> 00:26:51.466
the wavelengths off
the packet here,

00:26:51.466 --> 00:26:54.418
and we could have also
just thought of it as,

00:26:54.418 --> 00:26:58.354
when does the atomic
ensemble become

00:26:58.354 --> 00:27:00.322
bigger than the optical rate?

00:27:00.322 --> 00:27:02.290
But here, we are [INAUDIBLE].

00:27:02.290 --> 00:27:06.245
PROFESSOR: I think
for consistency-- I'll

00:27:06.245 --> 00:27:07.250
give you a quick answer.

00:27:07.250 --> 00:27:10.260
I should think about it
longer, but what we usually

00:27:10.260 --> 00:27:12.450
assume when we describe
atoms by wave packets,

00:27:12.450 --> 00:27:15.680
we assume the atoms
are not cooled

00:27:15.680 --> 00:27:17.860
below the so-called
recoil limit.

00:27:17.860 --> 00:27:20.760
So we assume that the thermal
de Broglie wavelengths

00:27:20.760 --> 00:27:23.410
is shorter than the
