00:27:23.410 --> 00:27:27.232
And so then if you would
say, you would expect also

00:27:27.232 --> 00:27:29.440
that there would be something
happening when the wave

00:27:29.440 --> 00:27:32.370
packet spreads out by
an optical wavelength,

00:27:32.370 --> 00:27:33.670
I want to think about it more.

00:27:33.670 --> 00:27:35.800
But the quick answer
is, just assume

00:27:35.800 --> 00:27:37.967
what is usually the
semi-classical limit

00:27:37.967 --> 00:27:39.745
of these kind of
pictures, where we

00:27:39.745 --> 00:27:43.900
assume that we have a hierarchy
that the thermal de Broglie

00:27:43.900 --> 00:27:46.242
wavelength is much larger
than the size of the atoms

00:27:46.242 --> 00:27:47.950
but smaller than the
optical wavelengths.

00:27:47.950 --> 00:27:49.227
AUDIENCE: That makes sense.

00:27:49.227 --> 00:27:50.852
PROFESSOR: A few
things happen, really,

00:27:50.852 --> 00:27:54.030
in intuitive pictures
when you cool atoms

00:27:54.030 --> 00:27:55.440
before the recoil limit.

00:27:58.221 --> 00:27:58.720
OK.

00:27:58.720 --> 00:28:04.690
There's one reason why I would
like to express it to you.

00:28:04.690 --> 00:28:09.270
Armed with that knowledge,
if I would now ask you--

00:28:09.270 --> 00:28:14.220
you have a trapped
Bose-Einstein condensate,

00:28:14.220 --> 00:28:18.814
and you take the spectrum.

00:28:18.814 --> 00:28:20.563
What is the Doppler
widths of the spectrum

00:28:20.563 --> 00:28:21.813
of a Bose-Einstein condensate?

00:28:25.139 --> 00:28:27.180
[INAUDIBLE] extra
Maxwell-Boltzmann distribution.

00:28:27.180 --> 00:28:27.846
No.

00:28:27.846 --> 00:28:29.150
The condensate is different.

00:28:29.150 --> 00:28:32.430
It's in one quantum state.

00:28:32.430 --> 00:28:36.710
But now you can
choose your picture.

00:28:36.710 --> 00:28:43.130
One picture you can take is
you can say, the de Broglie

00:28:43.130 --> 00:28:48.440
wavelengths here has to be--
you know, the wave packet loses

00:28:48.440 --> 00:28:50.590
overlap when the
excited state moves

00:28:50.590 --> 00:28:52.250
one de Broglie wavelength.

00:28:52.250 --> 00:28:54.360
But the condensate
is fully coherent.

00:28:54.360 --> 00:28:56.930
So you would now say,
maybe I should think about

00:28:56.930 --> 00:28:59.750
if-- if the
condensate part of it

00:28:59.750 --> 00:29:04.850
is coupled to the excited
state, and with a recoil,

00:29:04.850 --> 00:29:07.800
the excited state
component has moved

00:29:07.800 --> 00:29:10.900
the size of the condensate,
replacing the de Broglie

00:29:10.900 --> 00:29:14.380
wavelengths by the
size of the condensate.

00:29:14.380 --> 00:29:16.340
And this is a correct answer.

00:29:16.340 --> 00:29:20.380
You would then find out
what is, quotation mark,

00:29:20.380 --> 00:29:24.206
the Doppler broadening
of a condensate.

00:29:24.206 --> 00:29:25.705
Of course, you could
have also said,

00:29:25.705 --> 00:29:27.950
the condensate is
a certain size,

00:29:27.950 --> 00:29:31.240
h bar divided by the size is
the momentum spread if you

00:29:31.240 --> 00:29:33.300
do Heisenberg's
uncertainty relation.

00:29:33.300 --> 00:29:35.790
And now I plug in
this momentum spread

00:29:35.790 --> 00:29:38.650
into a formula for the
Doppler broadening.

00:29:38.650 --> 00:29:40.320
And you would get
the same result.

00:29:40.320 --> 00:29:43.000
But especially when you think
in terms of a coherent wave

00:29:43.000 --> 00:29:47.400
function, this picture of losing
overlap between the two parts

00:29:47.400 --> 00:29:51.190
of the wave packets is very
intuitive, very useful.

00:29:51.190 --> 00:29:55.970
And it actually guided
a lot of our intuition

00:29:55.970 --> 00:29:59.254
when we looked at the
limitations of super radians

00:29:59.254 --> 00:30:02.218
and optical spectroscopy with
Bose-Einstein condensates.

00:30:05.680 --> 00:30:06.906
Any questions?

00:30:11.590 --> 00:30:12.110
OK.

00:30:12.110 --> 00:30:16.315
So now we are ready to
take it to the next level.

00:30:16.315 --> 00:30:21.120
When I told you that
the spectral widths

00:30:21.120 --> 00:30:23.370
is the inverse of
the coherence time.

00:30:23.370 --> 00:30:25.860
And one way to think
about the coherence time

00:30:25.860 --> 00:30:30.040
is that the particles spread
out over one wavelength.

00:30:30.040 --> 00:30:34.390
So if you take this
thought seriously and say,

00:30:34.390 --> 00:30:38.792
what happens if I confine atoms
in a container or an atom trap

00:30:38.792 --> 00:30:41.264
to less than the
optical wavelengths,

00:30:41.264 --> 00:30:42.680
then you would
say, they can never

00:30:42.680 --> 00:30:45.190
spread out by an
optical wavelength.

00:30:45.190 --> 00:30:49.280
Does it mean that the
coherence time is now infinite

00:30:49.280 --> 00:30:53.790
and that we can do spectroscopy,
which is no longer affected

00:30:53.790 --> 00:30:58.550
in any way by
Doppler broadening.

00:30:58.550 --> 00:31:01.240
Well, what I just
motivated in words

00:31:01.240 --> 00:31:05.020
is the so-called Lamb-Dicke
limit of tight confinement.

00:31:05.020 --> 00:31:08.230
And as I want to show
you now, yes indeed,

00:31:08.230 --> 00:31:10.560
you have a very,
very sharp line which

00:31:10.560 --> 00:31:14.350
is not broadened by
Doppler broadening, which

00:31:14.350 --> 00:31:16.960
is not shifted by
the recoil shift.

00:31:16.960 --> 00:31:19.590
It's really the unperturbed
line of the atom which

00:31:19.590 --> 00:31:23.030
can be probed by confining
the atoms to less

00:31:23.030 --> 00:31:23.890
than a wavelength.

00:31:27.730 --> 00:31:32.950
So therefore, let's
now discuss the line

00:31:32.950 --> 00:31:37.150
shape of confined particles.

00:31:46.645 --> 00:31:48.020
So what I want to
present you now

00:31:48.020 --> 00:31:52.070
is we have particles trapped
in a harmonic oscillator.

00:31:52.070 --> 00:31:54.130
And in one limit, which
I want to explain you,

00:31:54.130 --> 00:32:00.830
we should just find the normal
Gaussian Doppler profile

00:32:00.830 --> 00:32:03.910
which we have
obtained for free gas.

00:32:03.910 --> 00:32:06.950
This must be the limit when
the [INAUDIBLE] confinement is

00:32:06.950 --> 00:32:08.020
very weak.

00:32:08.020 --> 00:32:12.490
But for tight confinement,
we should actually find,

00:32:12.490 --> 00:32:15.230
unless we assume other
means of line broadening,

00:32:15.230 --> 00:32:17.510
a delta function
spectral feature.

00:32:17.510 --> 00:32:20.170
And I will explain to
you that this is actually

00:32:20.170 --> 00:32:23.360
the same as the
Mossbauer effect.

00:32:23.360 --> 00:32:25.660
It's a Mossbauer line
due to the confinement.

00:32:30.260 --> 00:32:38.040
So therefore, to have
trapped particles

00:32:38.040 --> 00:32:53.854
allows us to go to the
ultimate limit in precision

00:32:53.854 --> 00:32:54.395
spectroscopy.

00:32:58.080 --> 00:33:02.420
What happens when you
have trapped particles--

00:33:02.420 --> 00:33:05.580
the Mossbauer effect,
which I mentioned,

00:33:05.580 --> 00:33:09.210
or simply the effect of
confinement-- in other words,

00:33:09.210 --> 00:33:13.600
the trapping potential
is completely

00:33:13.600 --> 00:33:19.910
eliminating the Doppler effect.

00:33:19.910 --> 00:33:21.430
But I want to be specific.

00:33:21.430 --> 00:33:23.863
It only eliminates the
first-order Doppler effect.

00:33:27.180 --> 00:33:29.940
Everything I just did with
the correlation function

00:33:29.940 --> 00:33:32.940
assumed first-order
Doppler effect.

00:33:32.940 --> 00:33:49.010
If you want to get rid of the
second-order Doppler effect,

00:33:49.010 --> 00:33:51.310
then you need some
form of proving.

00:33:51.310 --> 00:33:52.810
But usually, when
you do experiments

00:33:52.810 --> 00:33:55.990
with trapped particles, you
do confinement and cooling

00:33:55.990 --> 00:33:56.740
at the same time.

00:34:05.590 --> 00:34:06.210
OK.

00:34:06.210 --> 00:34:09.960
Let me start out with
very basic things.

00:34:13.639 --> 00:34:16.635
So let's talk about the spectrum
of an oscillating emitter.

00:34:24.630 --> 00:34:29.316
If we have an atom, it undergoes
a transition from excited state

00:34:29.316 --> 00:34:33.909
b to excited state a,
this is an internal state.

00:34:33.909 --> 00:34:36.440
But now we want
to include motion.

00:34:36.440 --> 00:34:39.650
And we have to include the
external degree of freedom.

00:34:39.650 --> 00:34:42.930
And for our discussion right
now, the external degree

00:34:42.930 --> 00:34:46.090
of freedom is [INAUDIBLE]
trapping potential.

00:34:46.090 --> 00:34:50.330
So now we look at the
combined system, combined--

00:34:50.330 --> 00:34:52.310
we can say Hubert
space, which combines

00:34:52.310 --> 00:34:55.120
external and internal motion.

00:34:55.120 --> 00:34:59.090
And of course, the external
motion is now quantized.

00:35:03.960 --> 00:35:08.355
I can't assume, but it doesn't
really add anything to it

00:35:08.355 --> 00:35:09.980
at this point-- that
the trap frequency

00:35:09.980 --> 00:35:13.400
and the ground and excited
state are different.

00:35:13.400 --> 00:35:16.755
I simply assume that
the trap frequency omega

00:35:16.755 --> 00:35:19.080
trap is the same.

00:35:19.080 --> 00:35:23.620
This, of course, is excellently
fulfilled in ion traps.

00:35:23.620 --> 00:35:27.920
If you reduce spectroscopy of
neutral atoms in a dipole trap,

00:35:27.920 --> 00:35:31.660
of course, the ground
and excited state

00:35:31.660 --> 00:35:34.250
may experience a
different AC stark shift.

00:35:34.250 --> 00:35:37.220
And then you have to account
for two different frequencies.

00:35:37.220 --> 00:35:39.550
But let me just make this
simplifying assumption.

00:35:46.010 --> 00:35:53.690
So if you assume that
an atom emits radiation,

00:35:53.690 --> 00:35:57.260
it will, for energy
conservation,

00:35:57.260 --> 00:36:00.030
emit at the electronic energy.

00:36:00.030 --> 00:36:10.530
But then there is an extra
term, which, in general, is

00:36:10.530 --> 00:36:12.380
the energy of the
external motion,

00:36:12.380 --> 00:36:16.530
or the trapping potential
for the initial state

00:36:16.530 --> 00:36:18.500
minus the final state.

00:36:18.500 --> 00:36:22.530
And if we now make our
simplifying assumption

00:36:22.530 --> 00:36:25.000
that everything is harmonic,
that hyper-potential

00:36:25.000 --> 00:36:27.570
is harmonic, and the
trapping frequency

00:36:27.570 --> 00:36:31.920
is the same in the excited
state and the ground state,

00:36:31.920 --> 00:36:37.852
we simply have the electronic
energy plus n quanta--

00:36:37.852 --> 00:36:41.170
n is the change of the number of
quanta of the harmonic motion.

00:36:45.470 --> 00:36:48.610
I want to point out,
it looks so trivial.

00:36:48.610 --> 00:36:52.280
But you should at least
think for a second

00:36:52.280 --> 00:36:58.230
about this statement, that this
formula includes the Doppler

00:36:58.230 --> 00:36:59.586
shift and the recoil shift.

00:37:14.470 --> 00:37:18.282
And of course, this is trivial,
because we are talking here

00:37:18.282 --> 00:37:21.370
about the total energy
of the external state,

00:37:21.370 --> 00:37:23.990
the total energy of the final
state after photon emission.

00:37:23.990 --> 00:37:27.160
And the energy and
the trapping potential

00:37:27.160 --> 00:37:30.790
includes all the kinetic
energy of the particle, which

00:37:30.790 --> 00:37:33.270
includes whatever comes
from [INAUDIBLE] velocity

00:37:33.270 --> 00:37:35.329
or from the motion of the atom.

00:37:39.550 --> 00:37:49.670
So therefore, we obtain what is
called the sideband spectrum.

00:37:53.819 --> 00:37:56.910
I'll just show you
a stick diagram.

00:37:56.910 --> 00:38:01.220
Here is the
electronic transition.

00:38:01.220 --> 00:38:04.550
And then we have sidebands.

00:38:08.380 --> 00:38:10.310
And the spacing
of those sidebands

00:38:10.310 --> 00:38:13.640
is nothing else than the
harmonic oscillator frequency.

00:38:17.600 --> 00:38:18.225
Any questions?

00:38:21.800 --> 00:38:23.620
At that level, I want
you to appreciate

00:38:23.620 --> 00:38:27.080
that this is radically different
from Doppler broadening.

00:38:27.080 --> 00:38:28.580
There is no Doppler broadening.

00:38:28.580 --> 00:38:32.365
By fully quantizing the motion
in the harmonic oscillator,

00:38:32.365 --> 00:38:36.210
we obtain a discrete spectrum.

00:38:36.210 --> 00:38:38.810
And what I want to show
you is when we calculate

00:38:38.810 --> 00:38:42.460
the intensity in the peak
for strong confinement,

00:38:42.460 --> 00:38:44.770
almost all of the intensity's
in the central peak.

00:38:44.770 --> 00:38:48.020
And therefore, there is
no Doppler broadening.

00:38:48.020 --> 00:38:50.350
But I want to later
show you how we

00:38:50.350 --> 00:38:53.090
can go from the discrete
spectrum back to the Doppler

00:38:53.090 --> 00:38:56.235
broadening which we just
described in free space.

00:39:07.719 --> 00:39:09.760
You should say, well, but
the motion, the recall,

00:39:09.760 --> 00:39:11.440
it must come in.

00:39:11.440 --> 00:39:12.570
Where is it?

00:39:12.570 --> 00:39:15.270
Well, it's not in
this stick diagram.

00:39:15.270 --> 00:39:19.460
But the sticks are
the only possibilities

00:39:19.460 --> 00:39:23.459
for the possible photon
frequencies or photon energies.

00:39:23.459 --> 00:39:25.250
But the question is,
what is the amplitude?

00:39:25.250 --> 00:39:28.554
What is the probability
that this will happen?

00:39:28.554 --> 00:39:30.220
And you already see
where I'm aiming to.

00:39:30.220 --> 00:39:32.011
In the limit that we
have many, many sticks

00:39:32.011 --> 00:39:34.020
and we are not
resolving the sticks,

00:39:34.020 --> 00:39:36.650
we will get back to them in the
standard Doppler broadening.

00:39:36.650 --> 00:39:39.770
So the big question is, how
many of those sticks do we have?

00:39:39.770 --> 00:39:42.570
Are we in the limit where
things are heavily discrete?

00:39:42.570 --> 00:39:43.660
This is our new limit?

00:39:43.660 --> 00:39:46.380
Or do we have
many, many of them?

00:39:46.380 --> 00:39:48.725
So therefore, the recoil
and the velocity, they

00:39:48.725 --> 00:39:53.430
really enter when we
calculate the intensity.

00:39:53.430 --> 00:39:57.430
And whatever our formulation
is with Fermi's golden rule,

00:39:57.430 --> 00:39:59.755
the rate is proportional
to the relevant matrix

00:39:59.755 --> 00:40:01.240
element squared.

00:40:03.750 --> 00:40:07.218
And now I want to show you
how we calculate those matrix

00:40:07.218 --> 00:40:08.194
element.

00:40:08.194 --> 00:40:09.170
You had a question?

00:40:09.170 --> 00:40:12.336
AUDIENCE: But is it true
that each of these sticks

00:40:12.336 --> 00:40:16.816
has the intrinsic line
width of the atom?

00:40:16.816 --> 00:40:17.490
PROFESSOR: Yes.

00:40:17.490 --> 00:40:19.013
We come to that
in a few minutes.

00:40:21.990 --> 00:40:25.890
I ignore here the
spontaneous broadening just

00:40:25.890 --> 00:40:27.580
for pedagogical reasons.

00:40:27.580 --> 00:40:30.170
But a little bit
later, I will-- I first

00:40:30.170 --> 00:40:32.290
want to sort of discuss
the number of sticks.

00:40:32.290 --> 00:40:33.790
Do we have a few?

00:40:33.790 --> 00:40:36.386
This is sort of new, then
we have only few sidebands,

00:40:36.386 --> 00:40:38.300
and we have the
Mossbauer effect.

00:40:38.300 --> 00:40:41.831
If we have many, that's sort
of more the continuum, which

00:40:41.831 --> 00:40:44.080
we described with the classical
velocity distribution.

00:40:44.080 --> 00:40:45.390
That's my message number one.

00:40:45.390 --> 00:40:48.220
But then the next message
is, do we resolve the sticks?

00:40:48.220 --> 00:40:50.670
Do we have resolved
sidebands or not?

00:40:50.670 --> 00:40:55.410
And for that, the criterion
is, is the natural line widths

00:40:55.410 --> 00:40:57.446
large or smaller than
the sideband spacing?

00:40:59.730 --> 00:41:01.980
It's not just one parameter;
there are two parameters.

00:41:04.982 --> 00:41:06.940
One is which will be the
Lamb-Dicke parameter--

00:41:06.940 --> 00:41:08.530
how many sticks do we have?

00:41:08.530 --> 00:41:10.780
And the second question is,
do we resolve the sticks?

00:41:10.780 --> 00:41:12.821
And you can say there are
four different regimes,

00:41:12.821 --> 00:41:16.007
you know-- yes or no for
question one, or yes or no

00:41:16.007 --> 00:41:18.810
for questions two.

00:41:18.810 --> 00:41:21.350
Other questions?

00:41:21.350 --> 00:41:22.850
OK.

00:41:22.850 --> 00:41:26.040
So the rate is proportional
to the matrix element squared.

00:41:26.040 --> 00:41:30.950
And yes, we have all kind of
the matrix elements involving

00:41:30.950 --> 00:41:31.940
the internal degree.

00:41:31.940 --> 00:41:35.150
But the new thing is
the matrix element

00:41:35.150 --> 00:41:39.710
for the center of mass wave
function of the atom, which

00:41:39.710 --> 00:41:42.730
is-- you can see just
the emission where

00:41:42.730 --> 00:41:52.040
the polynomials of the
harmonic oscillator.

00:41:52.040 --> 00:41:56.890
So we have the eigen functions
for the harmonic oscillator

00:41:56.890 --> 00:41:59.540
between initial and final state.

00:41:59.540 --> 00:42:04.780
And what acts on the only part
of the electromagnetic field

00:42:04.780 --> 00:42:07.450
operator, which acts on
the position of the atom,

00:42:07.450 --> 00:42:09.860
is this term, e
to the minus ikr.

00:42:13.770 --> 00:42:16.290
OK.

00:42:16.290 --> 00:42:21.200
I mentioned already
that the new regime

00:42:21.200 --> 00:42:25.040
is that the
confinement is tight.

00:42:25.040 --> 00:42:28.200
So let's just look
at this situation.

00:42:28.200 --> 00:42:36.080
When kr is much
smaller than 1, then we

00:42:36.080 --> 00:42:44.370
can expand this exponential
into 1 minus ikr.

00:42:44.370 --> 00:42:47.130
And now I want to remind
you that the position

00:42:47.130 --> 00:42:52.170
operator, when we treat
the harmonic oscillator,

00:42:52.170 --> 00:42:56.160
is nothing else than
a plus a dagger.

00:42:56.160 --> 00:43:01.700
So therefore, if kr is
small and therefore we

00:43:01.700 --> 00:43:07.780
can do the first-order expansion
of e to the ikr, our spectrum,

00:43:07.780 --> 00:43:13.550
our operator is here-- 1 minus
e [? vector ?] a plus a dagger.

00:43:13.550 --> 00:43:20.300
And therefore, the
only possible sidebands

00:43:20.300 --> 00:43:23.020
are the one where the
change in harmonic

00:43:23.020 --> 00:43:25.630
oscillator quantum number
is plus or minus 1.

00:43:28.450 --> 00:43:35.305
So we are already
obtaining the result,

00:43:35.305 --> 00:43:39.200
which is called the
Lamb-Dicke limit when

00:43:39.200 --> 00:43:44.230
kr is much smaller than 1,
that we have a strong carrier.

00:43:44.230 --> 00:43:50.110
We have only sticks-- the
delta n equals plus, minus 1.

00:43:50.110 --> 00:43:53.460
And the intensity in
each of those sticks

00:43:53.460 --> 00:44:02.290
is actually proportional
to k squared r squared,

00:44:02.290 --> 00:44:09.214
which is nothing else than
the square of the extension

00:44:09.214 --> 00:44:10.380
of the atomic wave function.

00:44:13.740 --> 00:44:16.520
And k is 1 over lambda
bar squared, divided

00:44:16.520 --> 00:44:19.880
by the optical
wavelengths we get.

00:44:19.880 --> 00:44:24.685
So we see already-- I mean,
without any major formalism

00:44:24.685 --> 00:44:27.550
or mathematical
tools-- what happens

00:44:27.550 --> 00:44:30.615
in the limit of
tight confinement.

00:44:30.615 --> 00:44:33.820
The spectrum of confined
particles is eclectic,

00:44:33.820 --> 00:44:36.490
the spontaneous line widths.

00:44:36.490 --> 00:44:39.840
A delta function without
any Doppler shift,

00:44:39.840 --> 00:44:44.780
without any recoil shift, right
at the resonance frequency,

00:44:44.780 --> 00:44:46.220
electronic frequency
of the atom.

00:44:48.900 --> 00:44:51.713
The only thing
which is reminiscent

00:44:51.713 --> 00:44:53.170
of the motional
degree of freedom

00:44:53.170 --> 00:44:55.340
are those small satellites.

00:44:55.340 --> 00:44:58.770
But their intensity goes
to 0 with the extension

00:44:58.770 --> 00:45:01.570
squared over lambda squared.

00:45:01.570 --> 00:45:03.850
So therefore, if you
confine the particle

00:45:03.850 --> 00:45:06.790
to less than an
optical wavelength,

00:45:06.790 --> 00:45:10.800
the older picture I told
you, it can never spread out

00:45:10.800 --> 00:45:12.630
over wavelengths,
can never get out

00:45:12.630 --> 00:45:14.740
of coherence with
the drive field.

00:45:14.740 --> 00:45:16.840
And here, we have a
quantitative description

00:45:16.840 --> 00:45:19.690
that at that moment,
we can obtain

00:45:19.690 --> 00:45:23.150
spectroscopic information
about the resonance completely

00:45:23.150 --> 00:45:24.550
unperturbed by motional effects.

00:45:42.050 --> 00:45:44.711
Questions?

00:45:44.711 --> 00:45:45.210
OK.

00:45:45.210 --> 00:45:47.350
So that was maybe
the most fun part,

00:45:47.350 --> 00:45:50.560
the extreme limit and
you realize what happens.

00:45:50.560 --> 00:45:57.980
But now we want to sort
of fill in the gaps.

00:45:57.980 --> 00:46:00.637
I first want to sort
of contrast what I just

00:46:00.637 --> 00:46:02.595
described to you with a
semi-classical picture.

00:46:09.040 --> 00:46:11.770
The semi-classical picture-- if
you have an emitting oscillator

00:46:11.770 --> 00:46:17.860
or absorber and we have
electromagnetic plane wave,

00:46:17.860 --> 00:46:24.910
we can now ask, what is
the phase of the plane wave

00:46:24.910 --> 00:46:27.820
experienced by the atom?

00:46:27.820 --> 00:46:31.950
And of course, the
phase is affected

00:46:31.950 --> 00:46:35.184
by the motion of the
atom if we assume

00:46:35.184 --> 00:46:39.630
the atom moves [INAUDIBLE]
with harmonic frequency omega

00:46:39.630 --> 00:46:42.000
t and an amplitude x0.

00:46:42.000 --> 00:46:47.475
Then this here is the
phase seen by the atom

00:46:47.475 --> 00:46:50.540
in its own reference frame.

00:46:50.540 --> 00:46:55.970
And if I then define-- with
another quotation mark,

00:46:55.970 --> 00:47:00.900
because it's sort of something
which needs explanation.

00:47:00.900 --> 00:47:04.660
If I define an instantaneous
frequency, which

00:47:04.660 --> 00:47:07.761
is nothing else than the
derivative of the phase,

00:47:07.761 --> 00:47:12.130
then I'll retrieve the
normal Doppler broadening.

00:47:12.130 --> 00:47:14.438
So now you see where sort
of normal Doppler broadening

00:47:14.438 --> 00:47:16.270
would come in.

00:47:16.270 --> 00:47:19.563
But the question is, you
cannot measure an instantaneous

00:47:19.563 --> 00:47:20.250
frequency.

00:47:20.250 --> 00:47:23.450
It would violate
the Fourier theorem.

00:47:23.450 --> 00:47:28.470
But if we can apply-- if the
atom oscillates slowly enough--

00:47:28.470 --> 00:47:33.200
the motion is slow enough
that we can apply the concept

00:47:33.200 --> 00:47:36.910
that we can look at the
frequency the atom experiences,

00:47:36.910 --> 00:47:40.650
you would at least say, before
the atom changes its velocity,

00:47:40.650 --> 00:47:42.645
it should see a few cycles.

00:47:42.645 --> 00:47:46.960
If it oscillates fairly fast,
this concept, of course,

00:47:46.960 --> 00:47:48.070
cannot be applied.

00:47:48.070 --> 00:47:52.020
But at least you see where your
normal Doppler shift comes in.

00:47:52.020 --> 00:47:56.030
It comes in in the concept of
an instantaneous frequency.

00:47:56.030 --> 00:47:59.020
Of course, what we
should do now is

00:47:59.020 --> 00:48:02.598
we should not take the concept
of the instantaneous frequency.

00:48:02.598 --> 00:48:04.988
We should do rather
do it correctly.

00:48:04.988 --> 00:48:08.340
What we have is we see we
have the phase of the atom.

00:48:08.340 --> 00:48:13.240
So therefore, we
should-- by using

00:48:13.240 --> 00:48:15.736
the motion of the atom
for x, we should have

00:48:15.736 --> 00:48:18.470
formed Fourier transform.

00:48:18.470 --> 00:48:20.710
The Fourier transform
tells us what

00:48:20.710 --> 00:48:23.020
is the tonal spectrum
which the atom experiences.

00:48:25.590 --> 00:48:29.702
So therefore, we
take this plane wave,

00:48:29.702 --> 00:48:32.770
we put in the oscillatory
behavior of the atom,

00:48:32.770 --> 00:48:34.684
and then we take away transform.

00:48:41.145 --> 00:48:41.650
OK.

00:48:41.650 --> 00:48:46.430
So the electromagnetic
field seen by the atom

00:48:46.430 --> 00:48:52.530
is an amplitude which is
the cosine of the phase.

00:48:52.530 --> 00:48:56.920
And the phase has a
temporal dependence

00:48:56.920 --> 00:49:00.040
that's just the frequency
of the plane wave.

00:49:00.040 --> 00:49:03.500
But now the precision
involves the oscillation

00:49:03.500 --> 00:49:07.800
of the atom at the
[INAUDIBLE] frequency omega t.

00:49:07.800 --> 00:49:13.069
And what I've introduced
here is the data [? vector ?]

00:49:13.069 --> 00:49:14.360
is called the modulation index.

00:49:14.360 --> 00:49:16.550
This is the relevant quantity.

00:49:16.550 --> 00:49:20.480
It is k, which comes from
the plane wave, e to the ikr,

00:49:20.480 --> 00:49:22.465
times the amplitude of the atom.

00:49:22.465 --> 00:49:26.310
And so the modulation
index is nothing else

00:49:26.310 --> 00:49:34.170
than the amplitude of the atomic
motion divided by the reduced

00:49:34.170 --> 00:49:35.230
wavelengths of the light.

00:49:37.870 --> 00:49:42.400
Just if you remember for a
second, this extreme stick

00:49:42.400 --> 00:49:45.720
diagram where we had one big
stick and two smaller sticks,

00:49:45.720 --> 00:49:48.690
remember, the intensity
in the smaller sticks

00:49:48.690 --> 00:49:51.460
was the extension
of the atom divided

00:49:51.460 --> 00:49:53.310
by the wavelength squared.

00:49:53.310 --> 00:49:55.230
So we had exactly
the same parameter,

00:49:55.230 --> 00:49:59.180
but the previous description
assumed a quantized picture

00:49:59.180 --> 00:50:01.010
for the harmonic oscillator.

00:50:01.010 --> 00:50:04.120
I really used a and a daggers
in the atomic wave function.

00:50:04.120 --> 00:50:06.210
This is a semi-classical
picture where

00:50:06.210 --> 00:50:08.410
I treat the
oscillation of the atom

00:50:08.410 --> 00:50:10.520
in a classical description.

00:50:10.520 --> 00:50:15.410
But in both cases, of course,
the relevant parameter

00:50:15.410 --> 00:50:18.722
is the ratio over
which the atom moves--

00:50:18.722 --> 00:50:20.450
the amplitude of
the atomic motion

00:50:20.450 --> 00:50:23.860
or the size of the atomic
wave function in relation

00:50:23.860 --> 00:50:27.651
to the wavelengths of the light.

00:50:27.651 --> 00:50:28.150
OK.

00:50:28.150 --> 00:50:31.420
So we want to Fourier
transform this function.

00:50:31.420 --> 00:50:32.950
And this gives us the spectrum.

00:50:38.385 --> 00:50:40.005
I can show you
that the result is

00:50:40.005 --> 00:50:52.730
that we can have a Fourier
expansion of this amplitude,

00:50:52.730 --> 00:50:54.240
and it involves basal functions.

00:50:54.240 --> 00:50:59.160
So it is the basal
function Jm which tells us

00:50:59.160 --> 00:51:03.610
what the intensity is
in the n's sideband.

00:51:03.610 --> 00:51:06.420
And the argument of
the basal function,

00:51:06.420 --> 00:51:08.550
whether we take the basal
function at the origin

00:51:08.550 --> 00:51:16.024
or at a finite argument, is
given by beta modulation index.

00:51:16.024 --> 00:51:18.545
You can't immediately
[INAUDIBLE] in just two lines.

00:51:18.545 --> 00:51:20.960
We write the Fourier transform.

00:51:20.960 --> 00:51:24.755
All you have to use
is those identities

00:51:24.755 --> 00:51:28.671
which involve the
basal function.

00:51:28.671 --> 00:51:31.170
Whenever you have the cosine
of a sine or the sine of a sine

00:51:31.170 --> 00:51:34.960
and you Fourier
transform, you get,

00:51:34.960 --> 00:51:37.312
naturally, basal functions.

00:51:41.431 --> 00:51:41.930
OK.

00:51:41.930 --> 00:51:45.320
So let's just look
at the result.

00:51:45.320 --> 00:51:48.590
We talked about
the stick diagram.

00:51:48.590 --> 00:51:52.060
The stick diagram was actually
motivated quantum mechanically.

00:51:52.060 --> 00:51:56.585
But now we also find a stick
diagram purely classically

00:51:56.585 --> 00:52:00.630
because of the periodic
motion in the harmonic trap.

00:52:00.630 --> 00:52:04.010
But now what we obtain in
the semi-classical limit,

00:52:04.010 --> 00:52:07.850
we obtain what is the
height of each stick.

00:52:07.850 --> 00:52:11.960
Well, the height of the stick,
which is n sidebands away,

00:52:11.960 --> 00:52:15.590
is given by the square of
the n's basal function.

00:52:15.590 --> 00:52:18.690
And beta is the
modulation index.

00:52:18.690 --> 00:52:22.570
And if beta goes
to 0, that means

00:52:22.570 --> 00:52:24.330
the atom is not moving at all.

00:52:24.330 --> 00:52:26.130
The amplitude x0 is 0.

00:52:26.130 --> 00:52:28.770
This is the limit of
tight confinement.

00:52:28.770 --> 00:52:33.730
Then all basal functions
are 0 except the 0's order.

00:52:33.730 --> 00:52:36.870
And that means we are back
to a single delta function,

00:52:36.870 --> 00:52:39.023
a single stick in
our stick diagram.

00:52:55.320 --> 00:53:00.420
So let's now take the
result and discuss it.

00:53:05.890 --> 00:53:09.280
So how does the
spectrum look like?

00:53:09.280 --> 00:53:15.300
Well, I want to give you
two limits where the atom is

00:53:15.300 --> 00:53:17.050
extended much larger
than the wavelengths.

00:53:17.050 --> 00:53:21.940
This means large modulation
index beta and small modulation

00:53:21.940 --> 00:53:25.510
index beta.

00:53:25.510 --> 00:53:52.750
But first, in the limit where
beta is large-- for large beta,

00:53:52.750 --> 00:53:59.150
the argument of
the basal function

00:53:59.150 --> 00:54:11.235
becomes just cosine
beta minus phase.

00:54:15.490 --> 00:54:36.870
So if we use that-- if we assume
a thermal distribution where

00:54:36.870 --> 00:54:43.380
beta over kt d beta squared.

00:54:43.380 --> 00:54:46.240
So we take our spectrum,
and we just convolute it

00:54:46.240 --> 00:54:51.650
with a thermal distribution
of amplitudes x0, which

00:54:51.650 --> 00:54:54.850
is, of course, just
the Boltzmann factor.

00:54:54.850 --> 00:55:04.660
And in that limit, we
actually obtain a spectrum

00:55:04.660 --> 00:55:11.180
where the envelope of the sticks
looks like the Doppler width.

00:55:11.180 --> 00:55:16.330
So if those two
conditions are fulfilled,

00:55:16.330 --> 00:55:21.002
then we obtain the
normal Doppler widths.

00:55:21.002 --> 00:55:26.420
If, in addition, we assume
that the sidebands are not

00:55:26.420 --> 00:55:28.700
resolved, because the
natural line width

00:55:28.700 --> 00:55:31.090
is larger than the spacing.

00:55:31.090 --> 00:55:33.390
So if we assume
that in addition,

00:55:33.390 --> 00:55:35.060
then we just find
the normal Doppler

00:55:35.060 --> 00:55:45.107
broadening how we have
derived it as in free space.

00:55:48.000 --> 00:55:50.780
So normal Doppler
broadening is the limit

00:55:50.780 --> 00:55:54.404
of the large modulation
index, a thermal distribution

00:55:54.404 --> 00:55:59.240
of modulation index in the
case of not resolved sidebands.

00:56:05.110 --> 00:56:08.460
The opposite limit,
of course, is

00:56:08.460 --> 00:56:15.350
when beta is much
smaller than 1,

00:56:15.350 --> 00:56:19.150
it means the amplitude of
the oscillating particle

00:56:19.150 --> 00:56:20.960
is smaller than the wavelengths.

00:56:23.530 --> 00:56:27.050
I mentioned it a few times,
so I should write it down.

00:56:27.050 --> 00:56:30.320
This is the Lamb-Dicke regime.

00:56:30.320 --> 00:56:37.980
And then the relevant
approximation

00:56:37.980 --> 00:56:43.896
for the basal function
is in the limit.

00:56:43.896 --> 00:56:52.450
And this limit is 1 over n
factorial times beta over 2 n.

00:56:52.450 --> 00:56:58.620
And for the case that n
is 1, this is just beta.

00:56:58.620 --> 00:57:02.050
And the amplitude
squared is beta squared.

00:57:02.050 --> 00:57:04.650
It's x0 over lambda
squared, as we

00:57:04.650 --> 00:57:08.480
had discussed before in
the quantum mechanic unit.

00:57:08.480 --> 00:57:10.940
So you'll see that
to use matrix element

00:57:10.940 --> 00:57:15.430
for the harmonic oscillator or
use a semi-classical Fourier

00:57:15.430 --> 00:57:18.170
transformed with a basal
function, both lead

00:57:18.170 --> 00:57:21.080
to the same result, that
deep in the Lamb-Dicke limit,

00:57:21.080 --> 00:57:25.250
we have essentially three peaks.

00:57:30.380 --> 00:57:34.280
And the satellites
are quadratically

00:57:34.280 --> 00:57:38.062
small in the modulation
index squared.

00:57:41.930 --> 00:57:52.390
So this regime is particularly
interesting for atomic locks

00:57:52.390 --> 00:57:55.010
and for meteorological
applications

00:57:55.010 --> 00:57:56.720
if the sidebands are resolved.

00:57:59.950 --> 00:58:01.540
If the sidebands
are not resolved,

00:58:01.540 --> 00:58:04.880
you have sort of a line
shape which depends,

00:58:04.880 --> 00:58:06.885
let's say, on temperature,
because x0 squared,

00:58:06.885 --> 00:58:11.970
if it's the thermal excitation,
is proportional to temperature.

00:58:11.970 --> 00:58:14.690
So as you cool it
down, you will actually

00:58:14.690 --> 00:58:16.940
see that your line
shape changes.

00:58:16.940 --> 00:58:23.609
But the good thing is that
once you resolve the sidebands,

00:58:23.609 --> 00:58:25.150
the line shape of
the central carrier

00:58:25.150 --> 00:58:27.090
does not change anymore.

00:58:27.090 --> 00:58:29.390
And once you can
resolve the sidebands,

00:58:29.390 --> 00:58:31.640
you can just observe
the central carrier,

00:58:31.640 --> 00:58:34.430
and you obtain
spectroscopic information

00:58:34.430 --> 00:58:37.673
which is no longer blurred,
which is no longer affected

00:58:37.673 --> 00:58:39.770
by motion or by temperature.

00:58:39.770 --> 00:58:43.970
And that's, of course, a regime
where the atomic frequency

00:58:43.970 --> 00:58:45.844
standards want to operate.

00:58:51.740 --> 00:58:52.240
Questions?

00:59:07.550 --> 00:59:08.050
OK.

00:59:10.942 --> 00:59:12.388
Yes.

00:59:12.388 --> 00:59:15.930
Let me just write that down,
because this is important.

00:59:15.930 --> 00:59:34.420
For resolved sidebands,
you have sharp lines,

00:59:34.420 --> 00:59:35.720
no motional broadening.

00:59:45.460 --> 00:59:47.580
And the physics I
described to you

00:59:47.580 --> 00:59:53.610
is actually analogous
to the Mossbauer effect.

01:00:00.894 --> 01:00:05.580
In the Mossbauer effect, the
intensity of the recoil-less

01:00:05.580 --> 01:00:09.580
emission of this recoil-less
line is described

01:00:09.580 --> 01:00:16.060
by the [INAUDIBLE]
[? vector. ?] So in this case,

01:00:16.060 --> 01:00:21.076
the [INAUDIBLE] [? vector ?]
is 1 minus the probability

01:00:21.076 --> 01:00:22.840
for the two sidebands.

01:00:22.840 --> 01:00:26.170
So the same concept of
Mossbauer line and [INAUDIBLE]

01:00:26.170 --> 01:00:31.950
[? vector ?]
describes the physics

01:00:31.950 --> 01:00:33.294
for tightly confined particles.

01:00:43.020 --> 01:00:48.250
So if I use the analogy
to the Mossbauer effect,

01:00:48.250 --> 01:00:52.010
the Mossbauer effect is called
the recoil-less emission

01:00:52.010 --> 01:00:54.190
and absorption of x-rays.

01:00:54.190 --> 01:01:04.310
So what we have here is we
have a recoil-less absorption

01:01:04.310 --> 01:01:06.284
and emission of photons.

01:01:09.630 --> 01:01:11.850
Of course, the photon which
is emitted and absorbed

01:01:11.850 --> 01:01:13.160
has momentum.

01:01:13.160 --> 01:01:15.040
There should be momentum recoil.

01:01:15.040 --> 01:01:18.140
So the question is, where
does the momentum recoil

01:01:18.140 --> 01:01:23.600
go when the confined
particle emits or absorbs

01:01:23.600 --> 01:01:26.310
on the carrier of
the central line.

01:01:26.310 --> 01:01:31.620
How do we reconcile
the result I derived

01:01:31.620 --> 01:01:33.928
for you with momentum
conservation?

01:01:42.680 --> 01:01:45.000
A trapped particle,
tightly confined.

01:01:45.000 --> 01:01:48.270
And photon comes, has
momentum, the atom absorbs it.

01:01:52.380 --> 01:01:54.200
But the spectrum does
not show any evidence

01:01:54.200 --> 01:01:55.712
for recoil shifts and such.

01:02:01.465 --> 01:02:01.965
Colin.

01:02:01.965 --> 01:02:03.923
AUDIENCE: Must be absorbed
by the trap somehow.

01:02:03.923 --> 01:02:06.930
PROFESSOR: Must be
absorbed by the trap, yes.

01:02:06.930 --> 01:02:09.380
Your trap is anchored
in the laboratory.

01:02:09.380 --> 01:02:11.200
And you transfer the momentum.

01:02:11.200 --> 01:02:12.990
The atom is attached
to the trap.

01:02:12.990 --> 01:02:14.830
The trap is attached
to the laboratory.

01:02:14.830 --> 01:02:19.020
So the object which
takes over the momentum

01:02:19.020 --> 01:02:21.290
is your whole apparatus
or, in the extreme case,

01:02:21.290 --> 01:02:23.110
a whole building.

01:02:23.110 --> 01:02:26.140
And there is, of
course, a kinetic energy

01:02:26.140 --> 01:02:29.820
associated-- momentum
squared over 2 m.

01:02:29.820 --> 01:02:32.300
But the mass is now the
mass of the building.

01:02:32.300 --> 01:02:35.340
So therefore, there is
no energy associated

01:02:35.340 --> 01:02:38.180
with absorbing the recoil.

01:02:38.180 --> 01:02:42.260
So it is as if-- and this comes
back to some earlier remarks

01:02:42.260 --> 01:02:45.280
I've made-- is
that when you have

01:02:45.280 --> 01:02:48.850
this absorption in
the Lamb-Dicke regime

01:02:48.850 --> 01:02:51.170
is it is as if your
two-level system has

01:02:51.170 --> 01:02:53.850
an infinite mass behind it.

01:02:53.850 --> 01:02:56.530
And that's sort of the situation
how I told you you should often

01:02:56.530 --> 01:02:58.680
think about it,
you should separate

01:02:58.680 --> 01:03:00.890
effects of the internal
degree of freedom

01:03:00.890 --> 01:03:02.690
and the external
degree of freedom

01:03:02.690 --> 01:03:05.020
by just assuming
I can assume first

01:03:05.020 --> 01:03:06.980
that the atom has infinite mass.

01:03:06.980 --> 01:03:08.950
And once the atom
has infinite mass,

01:03:08.950 --> 01:03:11.650
the motion degree of
freedom doesn't matter.

01:03:11.650 --> 01:03:14.090
What I just explained to
you is a practical way

01:03:14.090 --> 01:03:17.570
to endow your particle
with infinite mass.

01:03:17.570 --> 01:03:21.690
Just connect it with type
confinement to your apparatus.

01:03:21.690 --> 01:03:24.160
And then for the
momentum exchange,

01:03:24.160 --> 01:03:26.860
there is a photon
field, it is actually

01:03:26.860 --> 01:03:30.550
the mass of the whole
apparatus [INAUDIBLE].

01:03:30.550 --> 01:03:31.240
